{"/service/ndnp/ak/batch_ak_harborseal_ver04/data/sn98059811/00279525760/1907110901/0407.xml":{"full_text":"Seward Weekly Gateway\nf,), S W ARIL A LAS K A. S A T U\u00ab\u00bbAY, XOVEMBKK HM>7._>\u25a0<>\u2022\nOPPOSITION\nTO HOME ROLE\nAlaska\u2019s Friends in Washington\nFear Question May not Be\nActed on This Winter.\nSPEAKER CANNON IN THE WAV\nSenators and Representatives Think\nCountr> too Sparcely Settled\nat Present Time.\nBy Cable to The Dally Gateway.\nWashington 1). C., Nov. Friends\nof Alaska in this city arc practically\nassured that the question of home\ngovernment for Alaska will not be\nfavorably acted upon during the ses\nsion of congress this whiter.\nThe argument in the senate will be a\nquestion of the constitutionality of\nthe question. In the House the feel\ning prevails tluit the country is too\nsparcely settled for self government at\ntin- present time. Speaker Joseph\nCannon i> also uncompromisingly op\nposed to the measure, and will endea\nvor to keep it from coming before the\nhouse.\nOLD KENTUCKY\nGOES REPUBLICAN\nElect Augustus E. W ilson Gover\nnor and State Officials\u2014\nLegislature Democratic.\nBy Cable to The Dally Gateway.\nL '.i Ky., Nov. b Returns\nfrom the state indicate that the re pub\nlicans have wrested the state govern\nment i\u2022 the democrats.electing A. E.\nWilsut .oveiT.ur and other state otli\nces. The legislature, however, will\nhave a dem crutic majority on account\nof the iu\u00bbld over senator-' and member'\nof the house elected at the last elec\ntion.\n5 heat/e Elected in Pennsylvania\nPhiladelphia. Nov. b Returns from\ntbroujfhout the state indicate that\nJoiin Mieut/.e, republican, was elected\ngovernor.\n(iuild Re-elected in .Massachusetts\nHeston. Nov. b In the state election\nyesterday a liyfht vote was cast. Gov\nerror- Burt is Guild, republican, wa>\nre-elected.\nElection Close In Haryland\nBaltimore. Md., Nov. b The elec\ntion in this state yesterday was very\nclose. The democratic ticket will\nprobably win.\nVirginia Puts Democrats in\nRichmond, Va. Nov. b\u2014The demo\ncrats elected nearly the entire legis\nlative ticket at the stale election yes\nterday.\nMississippi Elects Only Democrats\nJackson, Miss, Nov.\u2014The entire\nstate democratic ticket was elected\nyesterday.\nRepublicans Elect Supreme Judge\nOmaha, Neb. Nov. b Judge Reese,\nrepublican, was yesterday elected a\njus ice of the supreme court.\nJohnson Wins Again In Cleveland\nCleveland Ohio, Nov. b\u2014Tom John\nson was re-elected mayor of this city\nyesterday for the fourth time, winning\nby a plurality of 9,500 votes. This is\nconsidered a knock at President Roose\nvelt. who sanctioned and gave his in\nflence to Burton, the regular republi\ncan candidate.\nAnti-Mormon Wins in Salt Lake\nSalt Lake, Nov. b\u2014 In the city elec\ntion hold here yesterday J. S. Brans\nford, Anti-Morman candidate, was\nelected Mayor by 4000 plurality.\nREID SUCCEEDS\nWICKERSHAM\nOklahoma Man Named by Presi\ndent for Jud^e In Third\nJudicial Division.\nBy Cable to The Dally Gateway\nWashington, R. I'., Nov. 7 Presi\ndent Roosevelt today announced that\nhe had appointed Silas R. Reid of\nOklahinia to succeed Judge Janies\nWickersham as judge of the district\ncourt for the third judicial division of\nAlaska.\nJudge Reid to Take up Work Soon\nWashington. IX <A, Nov. 8- Judge\nSilas R. Reid, who was yesterday ap\npointed by the president to succeed\nJudge James Wickersham of the third\njudicial division of Alaska will leave\nfor the north as soon as he can possi\nbly arrange his private atlairs, and\nconsult with the Department of Justice\nregarding judicial matters in the ter\nritory. Judge Reid is a young man.\nbeing but 3* years of age, and is a\nlawyer of ability. He was a candidate\nfor attorney general on the republi\ncan ticket at the recent election in\nOklahoma, but was defeated.\nnore Judicial Candicates\nWashingtoni, D. P. Nov. I -The\nlatest candidates for the judgeship for\nthe Third Division of Alaska are\nJohn Miller of Seattle and Judge Mu\nrane of Nome. Alaska. Roth men\nhave strong hacking. Judge Murane\nwas the republican condidate for dele\ngate to congress at the election held\nin IfK\u00bbn.\nTAYLOR WINS IN\nSAN FRANCISCO\nCitizens Cast Ballots for Reform\nCandidates for City and\nCounty Offices.\nBy Cable to The Dally Gateway.\nSan l*Yanci\"CO, Nov. 0 The city elec\ntiin lieiv \\e>terda\\ was one of the\nmost hotly contested in many years,\nand resulted in a landslide to the\ngood government league ticket. Dr.\nK. It. Taylor the candidate for mayor\non this ticket had a waik-over, receiv\ning l'J.ooo plurality over H. Mc\nCarty, union labor candidate, and ID..\n000 over D. A. Kyan. republican, and\nHearst candidate.\nJ. A. Langdon, candidate for dis\ntrict attorney on both the republican\nand democratic tickets won, hands\ndown, receiving li 1,000 majority. This\ni> a victory for Heney and the district\nattorney\u2019s otlice. and an endorsement\n1 by the citizens of the prosecution of\ngraft.\nTammany Wins in New York\nNew York, Xov. 0\u2014The Tammany\nticket in thi> city anil county carried\nthe election yesterday by about 30,000\nmajority.\nROOT TORETIRE\nFROM CARINET\n3y Cable to Tbe Daily Gateway.\nWashington, I), i'. Xov.8\u2014Secretary\nHoot announced today that he would\nretire from the cabinet in a short time\ni on account of ill health.\n\nCorwin Carries Much Tin\nThe steamer Corwin has the dis\ntinction of taking out the largest\nshipment of tin from Alaska. Among\nher cargo was 80,000 Pounds of stream\ntin from Cape York consined to\nTacoma. This tin is of a high quality\nbeing valued at 42 cents a pound.\nPERKINSRYAN\nCONTROL CAUCUS\nDelegates to Juneau Convention\nin Seattle fix up Slate After\nLively Discussion.\nCONGRESSMAN JONES TALKS\nJohn Corson Selected to Lead Light\non floor in favor of Terri\ntorial Ogranization.\nBy Cable to The Dally Gateway.\nSeattle, Oov. 5\u2014The Noraedelegates\nheld a lively caucus last night which\nwas attended by nearly all of the Alas\nkans in Seattle. After a very hot con\nit est I\u2019erkins and Ryan received the\nendorsement for the caucus as candi\ndates for delegates to the nation re\npublican convention to meet next\ni sutner to name a candidate for the\nI presidency. John Corson, Steel of\nNome and Milroy of Candle creek\nwere placed on committee to draft res\nolutions to he presented at the Juneau\nconvention. Corson will probably\nlead the tight at Juneau for a plank in\nthe platform favoring territorial gov\nernment. It is thought that perhaps\nj Col. Reakins may bo induced to witli\ndraw a> candidate for delegate to the\nnational convention in favor of Capt.\nJohnson of Nome.\nCongressman \\V. L. Jones of the\nstate of Washington in a speech before\ntlie caucus last night declared himself\nI in favor of home rule for Alaska.\nCorson Opposes Perkins Slate\nSent tie. Nov. 4. The Nome dele\ngates to the Juneau republican con\ntention now in this city are not in\npeaceful and harmonious accord with\neach other. \\V. T. Perkins, Alex Ryan\nand John Corson are all working for\nthe nomination as delegate to the\nnational convention, and much hitter\nstrife is manifested by the various\nfactions. The delegates now in this\ncity will hold a caucus tonight at\nwhich time they will decide who will\nhe their candidates from the Nome\ndistrict to the national convention.\nCorson threatens that if he is not\nnamed in the caucas he will knife\nPerkins and Ryan on tin* lloor of the\nI territorial convention at Janeau.\nADVOCATES\nRAILROADS\nMajor Richardson W ants Trunk\nLines for Central Alaska to\nOpen up Country.\nBy Cable to The Dally Gateway.\nSeattle, Nov. 5\u2014Maj. Wikis P. Rich*\nj ardson of t he Alaska road commission\nwho is now in this city, strongly advo\ncates the building of a trunk line rail\nroad through central Alaska, in order\nto open up the Territory to prospectors,\ni miners and farmers. \\Y agon roads, he\nsays, should then be built from the\nvarious creeks and settlements to con\ni nect with the railroad.\nBRISTOL BAY FISHERMEN\nOPPOSE USE OF TRAPS\nSeattle, Nov. 8\u2014Fear is entertained\nby the fishermen and residents of Bris\n1 tol bay, Alaska, that the salmon in\nWood river will be exterminated if\nmeasures are not adopted by the gov\nernment for their preservation. The\nuse of traps by the fishing companies\nat the mouth of the river allows but\nfew fish to get to the spawning grounds\nand the salmon are becoming more\nscarce each year. The Bristol bay\nfisherman\u2019s union will send delegates\nto Washington to confer with Secre\ntary Straus of the Interior department\nregarding the matter and urge the\nabolition of all traps.\nh\nKATALLA ROAD\nGuggenlieims Make Formal State\nment to This Effect\nThis Morning.\nay Cable to The Dally Gateway.\nSeattle, Nov. 7- The Guggenheim*\nformally announce today that they will\nimmediately abandon the building of\ntheir road from Katalla on account of\nthe poor harbor at that place, and the\nimpossibility of building a breakwater\nthere, and will build from Cordova.\nM. J. Ileney, the well known rail\nroad contractor, who built the White\n1\u2019ass road has been awarded the con\naraet to construct the road. Ileney is\nnow in this city hiring men to go\nnorth and each steamer will carry\nlaborers to Cordova. Ileney himself\nwill leave in about two weeks and will\nrush the work all winter and expect\nto have twenty miles of road ready for\noperation by the lirst of the year.\nMency on Way to Corbova\nSeattle, Nov. K. C. Hawkins,gen\ngeneral manager of tlie Guggenheim\nrailroad in Alaska, arrived today from\nNew York and confirms the announce\nment that the Guggenheims have\nabandoned the building of their rail\nroad from Katalla on account of poor\nharbor and will make Cordova the\nsea terminus.\nM. J. Heney leaves on steamer Yu\ncatan today for Cordova with large\ncrew of men and material.\nTELEGRAPHERS\nLOSE IN FIGHT\nLong Drawn Out Struggle Comes\nto Lnd and Operators Re\nturn to Work.\nay Cnble to The Daily Gateway.\nChicago, Nov. S\u2014Official notice was\ngiven out yesterday afternoon that\nthe telegrapher\u2019s strike was declared\noff and that all operators would return\nto keyes.\nSeattle Operators Return to Work\nSeattle, Nov. S\u2014'The local operators\nhave voted to abandon the strike and\nreturn to work.\nTelegraphers Returning to Work\nChicago, Nov. 7 -Reports from va\nrious sections throughout the country\nindicate that the striking operators\nhave voted to end tlie strike and re\nt urn to work.\nVote to Declare Strike off\nNew York, Nov. 4\u2014The telegraph\noperators who have been on a general\nstrike for the past three months have\nfinally decided to call the strike off\nand return to work. At a general\nmeeting held here yesterday they took\na final vote and decided to go to work\nnext Wednesday. It has has not been\nmade public on just what terms the\nstrike was settled. An agreement was\nreached at a secret meeting between\nrepresent at ves of the telegraphers\u2019\nunion and of the telegraph companies.\nWILY JAPANESE\nWANT TROUBLE\nBy Cable to The Dally Gateway.\nWashington, D. C. Nov. 9\u2014Official\nadvices have been received by the\nState Department that the Japanese\nin the Hawain and the Phillipine\nIslands have pledged the Mikado to\nsupport him in case of war with the\nUnited States, and will rise up at any\ntime and start an insurrection with\nthe unfriendly natives. The matter\nhas been referred to the United States\nMinister at Tokyo.\nWILL NOT CALL\nEXTRA SESSION\nPresident Roosevelt Thinks It Un\nnecessary as Panic Is\nNearly Over.\nMAKES ADMISSION TO FRIENDS\nSays He May Have Been Partially\nResponsible for Present\nFinancial Panic.\nBy Cable to The Dally Gateway.\nWashington, D. Nov. h\u2014Presi\ndent Roosevelt decided this morning\nthat it would not he necessary to call\nan extra session of congress. For sev\neral days it has been thought that an\nextra session would have to he called\nin case a general panic struck the\ncountry as a result of the tightness of\nthe money market and the failure of so\nmany banks throughout the country.\nHowever, the crisis seems to have\npassed and many financial institutions\nare again opening their doors. The\npresident admitted to friends that\nthat he may have been partialis re\nsponsible for the financial panic by Hie\nprosecution ol law breaking corpora\ntions, yet it was not his intention to\ncause trouble or turmoil throughout\nthe country.\nGOVERNMENT AID\nFOR PRODUCERS\nMoney to Be Distributed Through*\nout Country to Relieve\nStrain on Banks.\nNow York, Nov. 7 -The govcrment\nhas decided to place money in various\nbanks throughout the country, eape\ncially in the agricultural states to be\nused to assist in the movement of\ncrops. For this purpose and to help\nout the present stringency in the\nmoney market troughout the country\nover forty million dollars in gold lias\nbeen ordered shipped from Europe.\nTrust Company Bankrupt\nPortland. Ore. Nov. 7\u2014The Title\nGuarantee Trust Company of this city\ni closed its doors yesterday and a re\nceiver was appointed by the Court this\nmorning to take charge of its affairs.\n(iold Coming to Rescue\nNew York, Nov. 4\u2014Bankers of this\ncity are expecting a general and satis\nfactory settlement of the affairs of the\nKnickerbocker Trust Company and\nj and other hanks of this city in a few\n1 days. Every steamer from Europe is\ni bringing large amounts of gold and\nthe runs on tlie various hanks are be\ning met each day.\n\nSeattle Bankers Mold fleeting\nSeattle, Nov. 4\u2014At a meeting of\nthe bankers of this city held on Satur\nday night it was decided that the\nl clearing house would issue certificates\nto all the hanks today.\nTo Investigate Bank Failures\nNew York, Nov. 8\u2014An investiga\ntion has been ordered by the govern\nment\u2019of all the banking institutions\nthat have failed during the recent\nfinancial panic. If it is found that any\nof tho national banking laws have\nbeen violated the officials will be vig\norously prosecuted and sent to prison.\nNever Reached Knik\nA. F. McCullura the railroad man\nfrom Montreal, who started for the\nMatanuska coal fields with Duke Har\nris as guide is still at Seldovia await\ning the Tyoonic. Several otner par\nties are also there waiting for the\nsame boat.","height":"27387","width":"17703"}}
